counting and enforces budget against a real AI API's actual response, you must call the real API and measure actual token usage.","test_description":"Call classify() with a typical document and extract token usage from the API response. Assert tokens_used <= configured_budget. Repeat with edge cases (long documents, special characters) to ensure budget is never exceeded in realistic scenarios against the real API.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Testing token consumption inherently requires real API calls (Agentic) to measure what is actually used. Mocked token counts would not catch real over-budget failures.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0.7,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"The core failure is the module returning an error to the caller when it should retry instead. This is error-handling logic that can be tested at Unit level: mock the API to return a rate-limit error (HTTP 429) on the first call and success on the second, then verify the module succeeds instead of propagating the error. However, timing correctness (whether the module actually waits the configured duration) requires System/Integration testing.","test_description":"Mock the API client such that the first call raises/returns a rate-limit error (429 or equivalent) and the second call succeeds with a valid result. Call classify(). Assert that the returned result is the valid classification (not an error), proving the module retried instead of failing. Optionally, mock time and verify the module waited the configured backoff duration.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Unit test catches the core retry behavior (did it retry?). System/Integration tests would verify wait timing. The minimum to catch 'error propagation instead of retry' is Un